h3. Summary
The [ThreadLimitHealthCheck|https://bitbucket.org/atlassian/support-healthcheck-plugin/src/HEAD/src/main/resources/support-healthcheck-plugin.properties?fileviewer=file-view-default#support-healthcheck-plugin.properties-6:9,13] class is incorrectly failing environments where the number of user processes configured is =4096. This is incorrect and not consistent with the recommendations to set this to >= 4096.

There may be scenarios where admins will configure this to 4096 and the test will fail.


h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Set up a JIRA instance with user processes set to 4096
# Run the JIRA health check

h3. Expected Results
# The check passes

h3. Actual Results
The below warning is thrown in the healthcheck:
{noformat}
The maximum number of processes for the user account running JIRA is currently 4096, which can cause performance issues. We recommend increasing this to at least 4,096.
{noformat}
 
h3. Notes
The [SupportHealthStatus check()|https://bitbucket.org/atlassian/support-healthcheck-plugin/src/HEAD/src/main/java/com/atlassian/support/healthcheck/checks/ThreadLimitHealthCheck.java?fileviewer=file-view-default#ThreadLimitHealthCheck.java-1,6:10,14:15,27,43:46,49:50,53] call is incorrectly doing a conditional check for {code}if (threadLimit.get().greaterThan(MIN_THREAD_LIMIT)){code} when it should be doing it as >=.

{code:borderStyle=solid}public SupportHealthStatus check() {
        final Optional<FileSystemInfo.ThreadLimit> threadLimit = fileSystemInfo.getThreadLimit();
        if (threadLimit.isPresent()) {
            if (threadLimit.get().greaterThan(MIN_THREAD_LIMIT)) {
                return healthStatusFactory.healthy(i18nResolver.getText("healthcheck.threadlimit.valid",
                        application.name(), MIN_THREAD_LIMIT));
            } else {
                return healthStatusFactory.failed(i18nResolver.getText("healthcheck.threadlimit.fail",
                        application.name(), threadLimit.get().toString(), MIN_THREAD_LIMIT), WARNING);
            }
        }
        return healthStatusFactory.healthy(i18nResolver.getText("healthcheck.threadlimit.undefined",
                application.name(), MIN_THREAD_LIMIT));
    }{code}

h3. Fix

Upgrade the *JIRA Instance Health* add-on to the latest version using *Manage add-ons*.
